To make a GET request with params in Next.js API using axios, you can pass the params as an object in the `params` property of the axios request configuration. Here's an example:

```javascript
import axios from 'axios';

// Define your API route
const API_URL = 'https://example.com/api';

// Define your Next.js API route
export default async function handler(req, res) {
  try {
    // Get the query params from the req.query object
    const { param1, param2 } = req.query;

    // Pass the query params as an object in the axios request
    const response = await axios.get(`${API_URL}/endpoint`, {
      params: {
        param1,
        param2
      }
    });

    // Handle the response
    res.status(200).json(response.data);
  } catch (error) {
    // Handle errors
    res.status(500).json({ error: error.message });
  }
}
```

In this example, assume your Next.js API route is `/api/yourRoute`, and you're passing two query parameters: `param1` and `param2`.

Make sure to replace `https://example.com/api` with your actual API URL and adjust the endpoint as needed.

By using `req.query`, you can access the query parameters passed to the API route. Then, the axios `get` method is used to send a GET request to the specified URL with the params object containing the query parameters.

Finally, you can handle the API response and errors as per your requirements within the `try` and `catch` blocks.

In Prisma, you can use the `findMany` method to retrieve multiple records from your database. To include related records in the result set, you can utilize the `include` option.

Here's an example of how to use `include` with the `findMany` method in Prisma:

```javascript
const result = await prisma.yourModel.findMany({
  include: {
    relatedModel1: true, // Include all fields of relatedModel1
    relatedModel2: {
      select: {
        field1: true, // Include only field1 of relatedModel2
        field2: true // Include only field2 of relatedModel2
      }
    },
    // Include more related models as needed
  }
});
```

In the above code snippet, replace `yourModel` with the actual name of your Prisma model. Use the `include` option to specify the related models you want to include in the result set.

You can include all fields of a related model by setting its value to `true`. If you only want to include specific fields, you can use the `select` option within the related model object and specify the fields you want to include.

Make sure to modify the code according to your specific model and related models. After executing this code, `result` will contain the retrieved records along with the included related models.

Note: Before using `include` in Prisma, ensure that you have defined the appropriate relations between your models using the Prisma schema.

To create a link that contains both the title and ID of a post, you can use Next.js's `Link` component and pass the necessary data as query parameters.

Here's an example:

```javascript
import Link from 'next/link';

// Inside your component
const post = {
  id: 123,
  title: 'Example Post',
};

const PostLink = ({ post }) => (
  <Link href={`/post?id=${post.id}`} as={`/post/${post.id}`}>
    <a>{post.title}</a>
  </Link>
);

// Usage
const MyComponent = () => {
  return (
    <div>
      <PostLink post={post} />
    </div>
  );
};
```

In the above example, we define a `PostLink` component that accepts a `post` object as a prop. The `post` object contains an `id` and `title` property.

Within the `Link` component, we pass the post's ID as a query parameter using the `href` prop. The query parameter is accessed using `req.query` on the server-side or `useRouter().query` on the client-side.

We also set the `as` prop to specify a more user-friendly and clean-looking URL, where the ID of the post is appended as a path parameter.

You can customize the anchor (`<a>`) tag as desired, such as adding additional styling or applying CSS classes.

Make sure to adjust the code according to your specific requirements and routes in your Next.js application.

To convert a title of a post into a link dynamically using JavaScript, you can create a function that takes the title and post ID as arguments and returns an HTML element with the post title as a link. Here's an example using a JavaScript function:

```javascript
function createPostLink(title, id) {
  const link = document.createElement('a');
  link.href = `/post?id=${id}`;
  link.textContent = title;
  return link;
}

// Usage
const title = "Example Post";
const postId = 123;

const postLink = createPostLink(title, postId);
document.body.appendChild(postLink); // Add the link to the desired element in the DOM
```

In the above example, we create a function `createPostLink` that takes the post title and ID as arguments. The function creates a new anchor element using `document.createElement('a')`. We set the `href` attribute of the anchor element to include the post ID as a query parameter and set the `textContent` to the post title.

After creating the link, you can append it to the desired element in the DOM using `appendChild` or any other appropriate method.

This implementation assumes that you are working within a browser environment. If you are using Node.js or a different environment, the usage might vary. Adjust the code according to your specific requirements and how you want to handle the rendering of the link.

